  <title>Examples B</title>
 
<paragraphs>
  <title>Electric Flux</title>
  
  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        A uniform electric field of strength <m>E = 100 \,N/C</m> is directed along the 
        +x - axis through a cylinder of length 1 m and radius 0.2 m. If the cylinder is aligned 
        along the x -axis what is the electric flux through each of its three surfaces?  
        What is the total flux through the surface of the cylinder?
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <image source="fig14.png" width="35%"> </image>
           <p>
        Given: <m>E  =  100 \,N/C;\quad L  =  1 \,m; \quad r  =  0.2 \,m. </m> 
        <me>
          \text{Area of the caps}\quad A_{1}=\pi r^{2} =  A_{2} =0.1257 \,m^{2} 
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{Area of the cylindrical surface}\quad  A_{3} =2 \pi r L =1.257 \,m^{2}  
        </me>
        <me>
          \text{Now,}\quad \Phi_{1} = \int\vec{E}\cdot\vec{dA} = EA_{1}  =12.5 \,Nm^{2}/C
        </me>
        <me>
          \Phi_{2} = \int \vec{E}\cdot \vec{\,dA}= - \int E \,dA =  -EA_{2} = -12.5 \,Nm^{2}/C
        </me>
        <me>
          \Phi_{3} = \vec{E}\cdot \vec{A_{3}} = 0 
        </me>
        <me>
          \therefore\quad \Phi_{T} =\Phi_{1}+\Phi_{2}+\Phi_{3}=0
        </me>
            </p>
    </solution>
  </example>


<example>
  <statement>
    <p>
      A uniform electric field <me>E = 30 N/C \hat{i}+ 40 N/C \hat{j}</me> is directed through a rectangular 
      object of length 3 m along the x-axis, of height 2 m along the y-axis, and of width 1 m along the z-axis. 
      What are the electric fluxes through the surfaces located at 
      <ol marker="a.">
        <li>
          <m>x = 3 \,m,</m>
        </li>
        <li><m>x = 0,</m></li>
        <li><m>y = 2 \,m,</m></li>
        <li><m>y = 0,</m></li>
        <li><m>z = 1 \,m,</m></li>
        <li><m>z = 0? </m></li>
      </ol>
       </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <image source="fig15.png" width="35%"> </image>
    <p>
      Given: <me>
        E = 30 N/C \hat{i}+ 40 N/C \hat{j};
      </me>
      <m> L  =  3 \,m; \quad W  =  1 \,m;\quad H  =  2 \,m. </m>
<me>
  \Phi = \int\vec{E}\cdot\vec{dA} = \int E\,dA\cos\theta
</me>
<ol marker="a.">
  <li>
    <m> A_{x}=WH\hat{i};\quad \Phi_{1}=EA_{x}= 60 \,N m^{2}/C</m>
  </li>
  <li><m> A_{-x}=WH(-\hat{i});\quad \Phi_{2}=EA_{-x}= -60 \,N m^{2}/C</m></li>
  <li><m> A_{y}=LW\hat{j}; \quad \Phi_{3}= EA_{y}= 120  \,Nm^{2}/C </m></li>
  <li><m>A_{-y}=LW(-\hat{j}); \quad \Phi_{4}= EA_{-y}= - 120 \, Nm^{2}/C</m></li>
  <li><m> A_{z}=KH\hat{k}; \quad \Phi_{5}= EA_{z}= 0 </m></li>
  <li><m> A_{-z}=LH(-\hat{k}); \quad \Phi_{6}= EA_{-z}=  0 </m></li>
</ol>
   </p>
  </solution>
</example>

  <example>
    <statement>
      <p>
        An electric field is given by the equation 
        <me>
          \vec{E} = 2yz\hat{i} + 3xz\hat{j} - 4xy\hat{k},
        </me>
         in the MKS system. What is the electric flux through a surface whose corners 
         are at (0,0,0), (0,1,0), (0,1,2), and (0,0,2)?  
      </p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <me>
          \vec{\,dA}=dydz\hat{i}
        </me>
        <m>\because</m> surface is in the y,z plane.
        <me>
          \Phi_{E}=\int\vec{E}\cdot\vec{\,dA}=\int E_{x}\,dA_{yz} =\iint 2yz \,dy \,dz = \int\limits_{0}^{2}\left(\int\limits_{0}^{1}2yz\,dy\right)\,dz 
        </me>
        <me>
          = \int\limits_{0}^{2}z\left(\int\limits_{0}^{1}2y\,dy\right)\,dz  
        </me>
        <m>\because z </m> is independent of <m>y.</m>
        <me>
          =\int\limits_{0}^{2}z\left.\left(y^{2}\right\vert_{0}^{1} \right)\,dz  =  \int\limits_{0}^{2}z \,dz 
          = \left.\frac{z^{2}}{2}\right\vert_{0}^{2} =2 Nm^{2}/C
        </me>
              </p>
    </solution>
  </example>
</paragraphs>

